In an aim to get upgraded to tokio 0.2 so that we can use its sync/mutex code (see #112) I present this MR that introduces the [Tokio Compatibility Library](https://tokio.rs/blog/2019-12-compat/) and the [futures-rs compatibility layer](https://rust-lang.github.io/futures-rs/blog/2019/04/18/compatibility-layer.html) to allow us to run tokio 0.1 and tokio 0.2 (**async/.await**) code side-by-side.

The code compiles and runs but the unit tests will be broken.

Notice that the server.listen method is now async:

```rust
    pub async fn listener<'a>(self, addr: &str) {
        let addr = addr.parse().unwrap();
        let listener = TcpListener::bind(&addr).unwrap();
        let mut connections = listener.incoming().compat();

        use futures03::StreamExt;
        while let Some(socket) = connections.next().await {
            self.process(socket.unwrap()).await;
        }
    }
```

One can run it with:

```rust
runtime.spawn_std(server.listener("127.0.0.1:2122"));
```

Here is the corresponding changes in [unFTP](https://github.com/bolcom/unFTP/pull/24)

The `vendor` subdirectory can be removed once [tokio-util's](https://github.com/tokio-rs/tokio/tree/master/tokio-util) lates AsyncRead/AsyncWrite compatibility changes are on [crates.io]().

Lots of cleanup still needed but the basic just of it is there. This serves as a basis to:

- Phase 2 - Introduce the async locking mechanisms to solve issue #112
- Phase 3 - All code to nice async/.await and remove dependency on Tokio 0.1 (which is already in progress by other team members)
